<setup>

  <math name="x1">0</math>
  <math name="x2">4</math>
  <math name="y1">0</math>
  <math name="y2">2</math>
  
  <function name="f" styleNumber="1"> 1/8 * x^2</function>
  <curve name="g" styleNumber="2">
    <function variable="t">t^2</function>
    <function variable="t">t</function>
  </curve>
  <point name="P" draggable="false" styleNumber="5">(4,2)</point>
  <point name="Q" draggable="false" styleNumber="5">(0,0)</point>

  <function name="fX">sqrt(x)</function>
  <function name="gX">x^2/8</function>
  <function name="pY" variable="y">sqrt(8*y)</function>
  <function name="qY" variable="y">y^2</function>  
  
  <math name="intValue">8/3</math>

</setup>  

  <p>
    Consider the curves given by
    <me>x = y^2, \ y = \frac{1}{8}x^2</me>
    which are shown in the following graph.
  </p>

<graph size="medium" xmin="-1" xmax="5" ymin="-1" ymax="4" showNavigation="false" fixAxes="true" displayXAxis="false" displayYAxis="false">
  $f
  $g
  $P
  $Q
  <label anchor="(2,1.7)"><m>x=y^2</m></label>
  <label anchor="(3,0.7)"><m>y = \frac{1}{8}x^2</m></label>
  <line through="(0,0) (0,1)" styleNumber="5"/>
  <line through="(0,0) (1,0)" styleNumber="5"/>
</graph>  

  <p> 
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the graph and algebra appropriately to find the exact points of intersection between the curves.  State each intersection point as an ordered pair in the space below; if there is more than one, separate them with commas.  
        </p>
        <p><answer><mathList unordered>($x1,$y1) ($x2,$y2)</mathList></answer></p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Observe that it is possible to find the exact area between the two curves in two different ways:  one that uses an integral with respect to <m>x</m>, and another that uses an integral with respect to <m>y</m>.
        </p>
        <p> 
          If we use vertical rectangles and integrate with respect to <m>x</m>, the rectangles have height <m>f(x) - g(x)</m> where 
          <m>f(x) = </m><answer>$fX</answer>,
          <m>g(x) = </m><answer>$gX</answer>,
          and the rectangles have width <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice credit="1">dx</choice>
            <choice>dy</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus, the area, <m>A</m>, between the curves is given by the integral 
          <me>
            A = \int_a^b [f(x)-g(x)] \, dx
          </me>
          where 
          <m>a = </m><mathInput name="aEntered"/>, <m>b = </m><mathInput name="bEntered"/>, and <m>f(x)-g(x) = </m><mathInput name="fmgEntered"/> <answer><award><when>$aEntered=$x1 and $bEntered=$x2 and $fmgEntered=$fX-$gX </when></award></answer>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p> 
          If we instead use horizontal rectangles and integrate with respect to <m>y</m>, the rectangles have height <m>p(y) - q(y)</m> where <m>p(y) = </m><answer>$pY</answer>, <m>q(y) = </m><answer>$qY</answer>, and the rectangles have width <answer><choiceInput inline>
            <choice>?</choice>
            <choice>dx</choice>
            <choice credit="1">dy</choice>
          </choiceInput></answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          Thus, the area, <m>A</m>, between the curves is also given by the integral 
          <me>
            A = \int_c^d [p(y)-q(y)] \, dy
          </me>
          where 
          <m>c = </m><mathInput name="cEntered"/>, <m>d = </m><mathInput name="dEntered"/>, and <m>p(y)-q(y) = </m><mathInput name="pmqEntered"/> <answer><award><when>$cEntered=$y1 and $dEntered=$y2 and $pmqEntered=$pY-$qY </when></award></answer>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Finally, choose one of the two integrals you found above and evaluate it exactly using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.  Report the resulting exact value of the area, <m>A</m>, below.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>A = </m><answer>$intValue</answer>
        </p>  
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>